# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: laravel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Laravel includes Eloquent, an object-relational mapper (ORM) that makes it enjoyable to interact with your database.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] When using Eloquent, each database table has a corresponding "Model" that is used to interact with that table.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] In addition to retrieving records from the database table, Eloquent models allow you to insert, update, and delete records from the table as well.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Before getting started, be sure to configure a database connection in your application's `config/database.php` configuration file.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] For more information on configuring your database, check out the database configuration documentation.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] If you're new to Laravel, feel free to jump into the Laravel Bootcamp.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] The Laravel Bootcamp will walk you through building your first Laravel application using Eloquent.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] It's a great way to get a tour of everything that Laravel and Eloquent have to offer.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] To get started, let's create an Eloquent model.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Models typically live in the `app\Models` directory and extend the `Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Model` class.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] You may generate various other types of classes when generating a model, such as factories, seeders, policies, controllers, and form requests.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Sometimes it can be difficult to determine all of a model's available attributes and relationships just by skimming its code.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Models generated by the `make:model` command will be placed in the `app/Models` directory.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] After glancing at the example above, you may have noticed that we did not tell Eloquent which database table corresponds to our `Flight` model.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] By convention, the "snake case", plural name of the class will be used as the table name unless another name is explicitly specified.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] So, in this case, Eloquent will assume the `Flight` model stores records in the `flights` table, while an `AirTrafficController` model would store records in an `air_traffic_controllers` table.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Eloquent will also assume that each model's corresponding database table has a primary key column named `id`.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] In addition, Eloquent assumes that the primary key is an incrementing integer value, which means that Eloquent will automatically cast the primary key to an integer.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] If your model's primary key is not an integer, you should define a protected `$keyType` property on your model.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Eloquent requires each model to have at least one uniquely identifying "ID" that can serve as its primary key.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] "Composite" primary keys are not supported by Eloquent models.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] However, you are free to add additional multi-column, unique indexes to your database tables in addition to the table's uniquely identifying primary key.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Instead of using auto-incrementing integers as your Eloquent model's primary keys, you may choose to use UUIDs instead.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] UUIDs are universally unique alpha-numeric identifiers that are 36 characters long.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] If you would like a model to use a UUID key instead of an auto-incrementing integer key, you may use the `Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Concerns\HasUuids` trait on the model.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] By default, The `HasUuids` trait will generate "ordered" UUIDs for your models.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] These UUIDs are more efficient for indexed database storage because they can be sorted lexicographically.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] You can override the UUID generation process for a given model by defining a `newUniqueId` method on the model.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] If you wish, you may choose to utilize "ULIDs" instead of UUIDs.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] ULIDs are similar to UUIDs; however, they are only 26 characters in length.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Like ordered UUIDs, ULIDs are lexicographically sortable for efficient database indexing.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] To utilize ULIDs, you should use the `Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Concerns\HasUlids` trait on your model.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] By default, Eloquent expects `created_at` and `updated_at` columns to exist on your model's corresponding database table.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Eloquent will automatically set these column's values when models are created or updated.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] If you need to customize the format of your model's timestamps, set the `$dateFormat` property on your model.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] By default, all Eloquent models will use the default database connection that is configured for your application.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] By default, a newly instantiated model instance will not contain any attribute values.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] If you would like to define the default values for some of your model's attributes, you may define an `$attributes` property on your model.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Laravel offers several methods that allow you to configure Eloquent's behavior and "strictness" in a variety of situations.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] First, the `preventLazyLoading` method accepts an optional boolean argument that indicates if lazy loading should be prevented.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] For example, you may wish to only disable lazy loading in non-production environments so that your production environment will continue to function normally even if a lazy loaded relationship is accidentally present in production code.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Also, you may instruct Laravel to throw an exception when attempting to fill an unfillable attribute by invoking the `preventSilentlyDiscardingAttributes` method.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Once you have created a model and its associated database table, you are ready to start retrieving data from your database.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] You can think of each Eloquent model as a powerful query builder allowing you to fluently query the database table associated with the model.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] The Eloquent `all` method will return all of the results in the model's table.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Since Eloquent models are query builders, you should review all of the methods provided by Laravel's query builder.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] You may use any of these methods when writing your Eloquent queries.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] If you already have an instance of an Eloquent model that was retrieved from the database, you can "refresh" the model using the `fresh` and `refresh` methods.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] The `fresh` method will re-retrieve the model from the database.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] The `refresh` method will re-hydrate the existing model using fresh data from the database.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] As we have seen, Eloquent methods like `all` and `get` retrieve multiple records from the database.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] However, these methods don't return a plain PHP array.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Instead, an instance of `Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Collection` is returned.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] The Eloquent `Collection` class extends Laravel's base `Illuminate\Support\Collection` class, which provides a variety of helpful methods for interacting with data collections.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] In addition to the methods provided by Laravel's base collection class, the Eloquent collection class provides a few extra methods that are specifically intended for interacting with collections of Eloquent models.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Your application may run out of memory if you attempt to load tens of thousands of Eloquent records via the `all` or `get` methods.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Instead of using these methods, the `chunk` method may be used to process large numbers of models more efficiently.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] The `chunk` method will retrieve a subset of Eloquent models, passing them to a closure for processing.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] The first argument passed to the `chunk` method is the number of records you wish to receive per "chunk".
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] The closure passed as the second argument will be invoked for each chunk that is retrieved from the database.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] A database query will be executed to retrieve each chunk of records passed to the closure.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] If you are filtering the results of the `chunk` method based on a column that you will also be updating while iterating over the results, you should use the `chunkById` method.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Using the `chunk` method in these scenarios could lead to unexpected and inconsistent results.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] The `lazy` method works similarly to the `chunk` method in the sense that, behind the scenes, it executes the query in chunks.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] If you are filtering the results of the `lazy` method based on a column that you will also be updating while iterating over the results, you should use the `lazyById` method.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] You may filter the results based on the descending order of the `id` using the `lazyByIdDesc` method.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Similar to the `lazy` method, the `cursor` method may be used to significantly reduce your application's memory consumption when iterating through tens of thousands of Eloquent model records.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] The `cursor` method will only execute a single database query; however, the individual Eloquent models will not be hydrated until they are actually iterated over.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Therefore, only one Eloquent model is kept in memory at any given time while iterating over the cursor.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Since the `cursor` method only ever holds a single Eloquent model in memory at a time, it cannot eager load relationships.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] If you need to eager load relationships, consider using the `lazy` method instead.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] The `cursor` returns an `Illuminate\Support\LazyCollection` instance.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Although the `cursor` method uses far less memory than a regular query (by only holding a single Eloquent model in memory at a time), it will still eventually run out of memory.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] This is due to PHP's PDO driver internally caching all raw query results in its buffer.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] If you're dealing with a very large number of Eloquent records, consider using the `lazy` method instead.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Eloquent also offers advanced subquery support, which allows you to pull information from related tables in a single query.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] For example, let's imagine that we have a table of flight `destinations` and a table of `flights` to destinations.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] The `flights` table contains an `arrived_at` column which indicates when the flight arrived at the destination.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] In addition, the query builder's `orderBy` function supports subqueries.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Continuing to use our flight example, we may use this functionality to sort all destinations based on when the last flight arrived at that destination.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] In addition to retrieving all of the records matching a given query, you may also retrieve single records using the `find`, `first`, or `firstWhere` methods.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Sometimes you may wish to perform some other action if no results are found.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] The `findOr` and `firstOr` methods will return a single model instance or, if no results are found, execute the given closure.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Sometimes you may wish to throw an exception if a model is not found.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] This is particularly useful in routes or controllers.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] The `firstOrCreate` method will attempt to locate a database record using the given column / value pairs.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] The `firstOrNew` method, like `firstOrCreate`, will attempt to locate a record in the database matching the given attributes.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] However, if a model is not found, a new model instance will be returned.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] Note that the model returned by `firstOrNew` has not yet been persisted to the database.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p01] When interacting with Eloquent models, you may also use the `count`, `sum`, `max`, and other aggregate methods provided by the Laravel query builder.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Of course, when using Eloquent, we don't only need to retrieve models from the database.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] To insert a new record into the database, you should instantiate a new model instance and set attributes on the model.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] In this example, we assign the `name` field from the incoming HTTP request to the `name` attribute of the `App\Models\Flight` model instance.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] When we call the `save` method, a record will be inserted into the database.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] The model's `created_at` and `updated_at` timestamps will automatically be set when the `save` method is called, so there is no need to set them manually.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Alternatively, you may use the `create` method to "save" a new model using a single PHP statement.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] However, before using the `create` method, you will need to specify either a `fillable` or `guarded` property on your model class.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] These properties are required because all Eloquent models are protected against mass assignment vulnerabilities by default.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] To learn more about mass assignment, please consult the mass assignment documentation.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] The `save` method may also be used to update models that already exist in the database.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] To update a model, you should retrieve it and set any attributes you wish to update.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Then, you should call the model's `save` method.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Occasionally, you may need to update an existing model or create a new model if no matching model exists.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Like the `firstOrCreate` method, the `updateOrCreate` method persists the model, so there's no need to manually call the `save` method.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] In the example below, if a flight exists with a `departure` location of `Oakland` and a `destination` location of `San Diego`, its `price` and `discounted` columns will be updated.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Updates can also be performed against models that match a given query.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] The `update` method expects an array of column and value pairs representing the columns that should be updated.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] The `update` method returns the number of affected rows.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] When issuing a mass update via Eloquent, the `saving`, `saved`, `updating`, and `updated` model events will not be fired for the updated models.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] This is because the models are never actually retrieved when issuing a mass update.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Eloquent provides the `isDirty`, `isClean`, and `wasChanged` methods to examine the internal state of your model and determine how its attributes have changed from when the model was originally retrieved.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] The `isDirty` method determines if any of the model's attributes have been changed since the model was retrieved.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] You may pass a specific attribute name or an array of attributes to the `isDirty` method to determine if any of the attributes are "dirty".
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] The `isClean` method will determine if an attribute has remained unchanged since the model was retrieved.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] The `wasChanged` method determines if any attributes were changed when the model was last saved within the current request cycle.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] The `getOriginal` method returns an array containing the original attributes of the model regardless of any changes to the model since it was retrieved.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] You may use the `create` method to "save" a new model using a single PHP statement.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] A mass assignment vulnerability occurs when a user passes an unexpected HTTP request field and that field changes a column in your database that you did not expect.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] For example, a malicious user might send an `is_admin` parameter through an HTTP request, which is then passed to your model's `create` method, allowing the user to escalate themselves to an administrator.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] So, to get started, you should define which model attributes you want to make mass assignable.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] You may do this using the `$fillable` property on the model.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Once you have specified which attributes are mass assignable, you may use the `create` method to insert a new record in the database.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] When assigning JSON columns, each column's mass assignable key must be specified in your model's `$fillable` array.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] If you would like to make all of your attributes mass assignable, you may define your model's `$guarded` property as an empty array.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] By default, attributes that are not included in the `$fillable` array are silently discarded when performing mass-assignment operations.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] In production, this is expected behavior; however, during local development it can lead to confusion as to why model changes are not taking effect.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] If you wish, you may instruct Laravel to throw an exception when attempting to fill an unfillable attribute by invoking the `preventSilentlyDiscardingAttributes` method.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Eloquent's `upsert` method may be used to update or create records in a single, atomic operation.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] The method's first argument consists of the values to insert or update, while the second argument lists the column(s) that uniquely identify records within the associated table.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] The method's third and final argument is an array of the columns that should be updated if a matching record already exists in the database.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] All databases except SQL Server require the columns in the second argument of the `upsert` method to have a "primary" or "unique" index.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] In addition, the MariaDB and MySQL database drivers ignore the second argument of the `upsert` method and always use the "primary" and "unique" indexes of the table to detect existing records.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] In the example above, we are retrieving the model from the database before calling the `delete` method.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] However, if you know the primary key of the model, you may delete the model without explicitly retrieving it by calling the `destroy` method.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] The `destroy` method loads each model individually and calls the `delete` method so that the `deleting` and `deleted` events are properly dispatched for each model.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Of course, you may build an Eloquent query to delete all models matching your query's criteria.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] In this example, we will delete all flights that are marked as inactive.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] When executing a mass delete statement via Eloquent, the `deleting` and `deleted` model events will not be dispatched for the deleted models.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] This is because the models are never actually retrieved when executing the delete statement.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] In addition to actually removing records from your database, Eloquent can also "soft delete" models.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] When models are soft deleted, they are not actually removed from your database.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Instead, a `deleted_at` attribute is set on the model indicating the date and time at which the model was "deleted".
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] The `SoftDeletes` trait will automatically cast the `deleted_at` attribute to a `DateTime` / `Carbon` instance for you.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] You should also add the `deleted_at` column to your database table.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Now, when you call the `delete` method on the model, the `deleted_at` column will be set to the current date and time.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] However, the model's database record will be left in the table.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] When querying a model that uses soft deletes, the soft deleted models will automatically be excluded from all query results.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Sometimes you may wish to "un-delete" a soft deleted model.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] To restore a soft deleted model, you may call the `restore` method on a model instance.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] You may also use the `restore` method in a query to restore multiple models.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Sometimes you may need to truly remove a model from your database.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] As noted above, soft deleted models will automatically be excluded from query results.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Sometimes you may want to periodically delete models that are no longer needed.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] To accomplish this, you may add the `Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Prunable` or `Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\MassPrunable` trait to the models you would like to periodically prune.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] When marking models as `Prunable`, you may also define a `pruning` method on the model.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] This method will be called before the model is deleted.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] After configuring your prunable model, you should schedule the `model:prune` Artisan command in your application's `routes/console.php` file.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Behind the scenes, the `model:prune` command will automatically detect "Prunable" models within your application's `app/Models` directory.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] You may test your `prunable` query by executing the `model:prune` command with the `--pretend` option.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Soft deleting models will be permanently deleted (`forceDelete`) if they match the prunable query.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] When models are marked with the `Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\MassPrunable` trait, models are deleted from the database using mass-deletion queries.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Therefore, the `pruning` method will not be invoked, nor will the `deleting` and `deleted` model events be dispatched.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] You may create an unsaved copy of an existing model instance using the `replicate` method.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Global scopes allow you to add constraints to all queries for a given model.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Laravel's own soft delete functionality utilizes global scopes to only retrieve "non-deleted" models from the database.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Writing your own global scopes can provide a convenient, easy way to make sure every query for a given model receives certain constraints.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] First, use the `make:scope` command to generate a class that implements the `Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Scope` interface.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] The `Scope` interface requires you to implement one method: `apply`.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] If your global scope is adding columns to the select clause of the query, you should use the `addSelect` method instead of `select`.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] This will prevent the unintentional replacement of the query's existing select clause.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Or, you may manually register the global scope by overriding the model's `booted` method and invoke the model's `addGlobalScope` method.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Eloquent also allows you to define global scopes using closures, which is particularly useful for simple scopes that do not warrant a separate class of their own.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] If you would like to remove a global scope for a given query, you may use the `withoutGlobalScope` method.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Local scopes allow you to define common sets of query constraints that you may easily re-use throughout your application.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] For example, you may need to frequently retrieve all users that are considered "popular".
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] To define a scope, prefix an Eloquent model method with `scope`.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Once the scope has been defined, you may call the scope methods when querying the model.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] However, you should not include the `scope` prefix when calling the method.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Sometimes you may wish to define a scope that accepts parameters.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] To get started, just add your additional parameters to your scope method's signature.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] Sometimes you may need to determine if two models are the "same" or not.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p02] The `is` and `isNot` methods are also available when using the `belongsTo`, `hasOne`, `morphTo`, and `morphOne` relationships.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] Want to broadcast your Eloquent events directly to your client-side application?
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] Check out Laravel's model event broadcasting.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] The `retrieved` event will dispatch when an existing model is retrieved from the database.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] When a new model is saved for the first time, the `creating` and `created` events will dispatch.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] The `updating` / `updated` events will dispatch when an existing model is modified and the `save` method is called.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] The `saving` / `saved` events will dispatch when a model is created or updated - even if the model's attributes have not been changed.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] Event names ending with `-ing` are dispatched before any changes to the model are persisted, while events ending with `-ed` are dispatched after the changes to the model are persisted.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] To start listening to model events, define a `$dispatchesEvents` property on your Eloquent model.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] This property maps various points of the Eloquent model's lifecycle to your own event classes.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] After defining and mapping your Eloquent events, you may use event listeners to handle the events.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] When issuing a mass update or delete query via Eloquent, the `saved`, `updated`, `deleting`, and `deleted` model events will not be dispatched for the affected models.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] This is because the models are never actually retrieved when performing mass updates or deletes.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] Instead of using custom event classes, you may register closures that execute when various model events are dispatched.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] If needed, you may utilize queueable anonymous event listeners when registering model events.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] If you are listening for many events on a given model, you may use observers to group all of your listeners into a single class.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] Observer classes have method names which reflect the Eloquent events you wish to listen for.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] Each of these methods receives the affected model as their only argument.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] This command will place the new observer in your `app/Observers` directory.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] If this directory does not exist, Artisan will create it for you.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] Or, you may manually register an observer by invoking the `observe` method on the model you wish to observe.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] There are additional events an observer can listen to, such as `saving` and `retrieved`.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] These events are described within the events documentation.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] When models are being created within a database transaction, you may want to instruct an observer to only execute its event handlers after the database transaction is committed.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] You may accomplish this by implementing the `ShouldHandleEventsAfterCommit` interface on your observer.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] You may occasionally need to temporarily "mute" all events fired by a model.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] You may achieve this using the `withoutEvents` method.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] The `withoutEvents` method accepts a closure as its only argument.
[src:laravel/11-x-eloquent-p03] Sometimes you may wish to "save" a given model without dispatching any events.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] All Laravel routes are defined in your route files, which are located in the `routes` directory.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] These files are automatically loaded by Laravel using the configuration specified in your application's `bootstrap/app.php` file.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] The `routes/web.php` file defines routes that are for your web interface.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] These routes are assigned the `web` middleware group, which provides features like session state and CSRF protection.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] For most applications, you will begin by defining routes in your `routes/web.php` file.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] The routes defined in `routes/web.php` may be accessed by entering the defined route's URL in your browser.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] The `install:api` command installs Laravel Sanctum, which provides a robust, yet simple API token authentication guard which can be used to authenticate third-party API consumers, SPAs, or mobile applications.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] The routes in `routes/api.php` are stateless and are assigned to the `api` middleware group.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Additionally, the `/api` URI prefix is automatically applied to these routes, so you do not need to manually apply it to every route in the file.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Sometimes you may need to register a route that responds to multiple HTTP verbs.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] When defining multiple routes that share the same URI, routes using the `get`, `post`, `put`, `patch`, `delete`, and `options` methods should be defined before routes using the `any`, `match`, and `redirect` methods.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] This ensures the incoming request is matched with the correct route.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] You may type-hint any dependencies required by your route in your route's callback signature.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] The declared dependencies will automatically be resolved and injected into the callback by the Laravel service container.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Remember, any HTML forms pointing to `POST`, `PUT`, `PATCH`, or `DELETE` routes that are defined in the `web` routes file should include a CSRF token field.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Otherwise, the request will be rejected.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] If you are defining a route that redirects to another URI, you may use the `Route::redirect` method.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] By default, `Route::redirect` returns a `302` status code.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] When using route parameters in redirect routes, the following parameters are reserved by Laravel and cannot be used: `destination` and `status`.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] If your route only needs to return a view, you may use the `Route::view` method.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Like the `redirect` method, this method provides a simple shortcut so that you do not have to define a full route or controller.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] The `view` method accepts a URI as its first argument and a view name as its second argument.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] When using route parameters in view routes, the following parameters are reserved by Laravel and cannot be used: `view`, `data`, `status`, and `headers`.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] However, sometimes you may want to define an entirely new file to contain a subset of your application's routes.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] To accomplish this, you may provide a `then` closure to the `withRouting` method.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Or, you may even take complete control over route registration by providing a `using` closure to the `withRouting` method.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Sometimes you will need to capture segments of the URI within your route.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] For example, you may need to capture a user's ID from the URL.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Route parameters are always encased within `{}` braces and should consist of alphabetic characters.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Underscores (`_`) are also acceptable within route parameter names.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Route parameters are injected into route callbacks / controllers based on their order - the names of the route callback / controller arguments do not matter.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Occasionally you may need to specify a route parameter that may not always be present in the URI.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] You may do so by placing a `?` mark after the parameter name.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] You may constrain the format of your route parameters using the `where` method on a route instance.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] If the incoming request does not match the route pattern constraints, a 404 HTTP response will be returned.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] If you would like a route parameter to always be constrained by a given regular expression, you may use the `pattern` method.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] The Laravel routing component allows all characters except `/` to be present within route parameter values.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Encoded forward slashes are only supported within the last route segment.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Named routes allow the convenient generation of URLs or redirects for specific routes.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] If the named route defines parameters, you may pass the parameters as the second argument to the `route` function.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Sometimes, you may wish to specify request-wide default values for URL parameters, such as the current locale.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] To accomplish this, you may use the `URL::defaults` method.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] If you would like to determine if the current request was routed to a given named route, you may use the `named` method on a Route instance.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Route groups allow you to share route attributes, such as middleware, across a large number of routes without needing to define those attributes on each individual route.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Nested groups attempt to intelligently "merge" attributes with their parent group.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Middleware and `where` conditions are merged while names and prefixes are appended.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Namespace delimiters and slashes in URI prefixes are automatically added where appropriate.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] To assign middleware to all routes within a group, you may use the `middleware` method before defining the group.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] If a group of routes all utilize the same controller, you may use the `controller` method to define the common controller for all of the routes within the group.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Route groups may also be used to handle subdomain routing.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Subdomains may be assigned route parameters just like route URIs, allowing you to capture a portion of the subdomain for usage in your route or controller.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] In order to ensure your subdomain routes are reachable, you should register subdomain routes before registering root domain routes.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] This will prevent root domain routes from overwriting subdomain routes which have the same URI path.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] The `prefix` method may be used to prefix each route in the group with a given URI.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] The `name` method may be used to prefix each route name in the group with a given string.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] For example, you may want to prefix the names of all of the routes in the group with `admin`.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] When injecting a model ID to a route or controller action, you will often query the database to retrieve the model that corresponds to that ID.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Laravel route model binding provides a convenient way to automatically inject the model instances directly into your routes.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] For example, instead of injecting a user's ID, you can inject the entire `User` model instance that matches the given ID.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Laravel automatically resolves Eloquent models defined in routes or controller actions whose type-hinted variable names match a route segment name.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Since the `$user` variable is type-hinted as the `App\Models\User` Eloquent model and the variable name matches the `{user}` URI segment, Laravel will automatically inject the model instance that has an ID matching the corresponding value from the request URI.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] If a matching model instance is not found in the database, a 404 HTTP response will automatically be generated.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Of course, implicit binding is also possible when using controller methods.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Typically, implicit model binding will not retrieve models that have been soft deleted.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Sometimes you may wish to resolve Eloquent models using a column other than `id`.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] When implicitly binding multiple Eloquent models in a single route definition, you may wish to scope the second Eloquent model such that it must be a child of the previous Eloquent model.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] When using a custom keyed implicit binding as a nested route parameter, Laravel will automatically scope the query to retrieve the nested model by its parent using conventions to guess the relationship name on the parent.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] In this case, it will be assumed that the `User` model has a relationship named `posts` (the plural form of the route parameter name) which can be used to retrieve the `Post` model.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] If you wish, you may instruct Laravel to scope "child" bindings even when a custom key is not provided.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Typically, a 404 HTTP response will be generated if an implicitly bound model is not found.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] However, you may customize this behavior by calling the `missing` method when defining your route.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] To complement this feature, Laravel allows you to type-hint a string-backed Enum on your route definition and Laravel will only invoke the route if that route segment corresponds to a valid Enum value.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Otherwise, a 404 HTTP response will be returned automatically.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] You may define a route that will only be invoked if the `{category}` route segment is `fruits` or `people`.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] You are not required to use Laravel's implicit, convention based model resolution in order to use model binding.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] You can also explicitly define how route parameters correspond to models.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] To register an explicit binding, use the router's `model` method to specify the class for a given parameter.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Since we have bound all `{user}` parameters to the `App\Models\User` model, an instance of that class will be injected into the route.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] So, for example, a request to `users/1` will inject the `User` instance from the database which has an ID of `1`.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] If a matching model instance is not found in the database, a 404 HTTP response will be automatically generated.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] If you wish to define your own model binding resolution logic, you may use the `Route::bind` method.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] The closure you pass to the `bind` method will receive the value of the URI segment and should return the instance of the class that should be injected into the route.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Alternatively, you may override the `resolveRouteBinding` method on your Eloquent model.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Using the `Route::fallback` method, you may define a route that will be executed when no other route matches the incoming request.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Typically, unhandled requests will automatically render a "404" page via your application's exception handler.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] However, since you would typically define the `fallback` route within your `routes/web.php` file, all middleware in the `web` middleware group will apply to the route.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Laravel includes powerful and customizable rate limiting services that you may utilize to restrict the amount of traffic for a given route or group of routes.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] To get started, you should define rate limiter configurations that meet your application's needs.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Rate limiters are defined using the `RateLimiter` facade's `for` method.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] The `for` method accepts a rate limiter name and a closure that returns the limit configuration that should apply to routes that are assigned to the rate limiter.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Limit configuration are instances of the `Illuminate\Cache\RateLimiting\Limit` class.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] This class contains helpful "builder" methods so that you can quickly define your limit.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] If the incoming request exceeds the specified rate limit, a response with a 429 HTTP status code will automatically be returned by Laravel.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Sometimes you may wish to segment rate limits by some arbitrary value.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] For example, you may wish to allow users to access a given route 100 times per minute per IP address.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] If needed, you may return an array of rate limits for a given rate limiter configuration.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] If you're assigning multiple rate limits segmented by identical `by` values, you should ensure that each `by` value is unique.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Rate limiters may be attached to routes or route groups using the `throttle` middleware.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] By default, the `throttle` middleware is mapped to the `Illuminate\Routing\Middleware\ThrottleRequests` class.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] However, if you are using Redis as your application's cache driver, you may wish to instruct Laravel to use Redis to manage rate limiting.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] To do so, you should use the `throttleWithRedis` method in your application's `bootstrap/app.php` file.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] HTML forms do not support `PUT`, `PATCH`, or `DELETE` actions.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] So, when defining `PUT`, `PATCH`, or `DELETE` routes that are called from an HTML form, you will need to add a hidden `_method` field to the form.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] You may refer to the API documentation for both the underlying class of the Route facade and Route instance to review all of the methods that are available on the router and route classes.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Laravel can automatically respond to CORS `OPTIONS` HTTP requests with values that you configure.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] The `OPTIONS` requests will automatically be handled by the `HandleCors` middleware that is automatically included in your application's global middleware stack.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Sometimes, you may need to customize the CORS configuration values for your application.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] This command will place a `cors.php` configuration file within your application's `config` directory.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] For more information on CORS and CORS headers, please consult the MDN web documentation on CORS.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] When deploying your application to production, you should take advantage of Laravel's route cache.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Using the route cache will drastically decrease the amount of time it takes to register all of your application's routes.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] After running this command, your cached routes file will be loaded on every request.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Remember, if you add any new routes you will need to generate a fresh route cache.
[src:laravel/11-x-routing] Because of this, you should only run the `route:cache` command during your project's deployment.
[src:laravel/laravel] The source code of Laravel is hosted on GitHub and licensed under the terms of the MIT License.
[src:laravel/laravel] Taylor Otwell created Laravel as an attempt to provide a more advanced alternative to the CodeIgniter framework, which did not provide certain features such as built-in support for user authentication and authorization.
[src:laravel/laravel] Laravel's first beta release was made available on June 9, 2011, followed by the Laravel 1 release later in the same month.
[src:laravel/laravel] On September 5, 2024, Laravel announced that they had received $57 million in Series A funding from Accel.
[src:laravel/laravel] Laravel 1 included built-in support for authentication, localisation, models, views, sessions, routing and other mechanisms, but lacked support for controllers that prevented it from being a true MVC framework.
[src:laravel/laravel] Laravel 2 was released in September 2011, bringing various improvements from the author and community.
[src:laravel/laravel] Major new features included the support for controllers, which made Laravel 2 a fully MVC-compliant framework, built-in support for the inversion of control (IoC) principle, and a templating system called *Blade*.
[src:laravel/laravel] As a downside, support for third-party packages was removed in Laravel 2.
[src:laravel/laravel] An increase of Laravel's userbase and popularity lined up with the release of Laravel 3.
[src:laravel/laravel] Laravel 4, codenamed *Illuminate*, was released in May 2013.
[src:laravel/laravel] It was made as a complete rewrite of the Laravel framework, migrating its layout into a set of separate packages distributed through Composer, which serves as an application-level package manager.
[src:laravel/laravel] Such a layout improved the extensibility of Laravel 4, which was paired with its official regular release schedule spanning six months between minor point releases.
[src:laravel/laravel] Other new features in the Laravel 4 release include database seeding for the initial population of databases, support for message queues, built-in support for sending different types of email, and support for delayed deletion of database records called *soft deletion*.
[src:laravel/laravel] Laravel 5 was released in February 2015 as a result of internal changes that ended up in renumbering the then-future Laravel 4.3 release.
[src:laravel/laravel] Laravel 5 also introduced a new internal directory tree structure for developed applications.
[src:laravel/laravel] Lumen 5.0 is the initial release of the Lumen framework, a light derivative of Laravel optimized for speed.
[src:laravel/laravel] This initial release is based on the Laravel 5.x series of PHP components, and following versions reflect the Laravel versions with which it shares common infrastructure.
[src:laravel/laravel] As of 2022, authors no longer recommend the use of Lumen for gaining these advantages, and promote Laravel Octane instead.
[src:laravel/laravel] Laravel 5.1, released in June 2015, was the first release of Laravel to receive long-term support (LTS).
[src:laravel/laravel] New LTS versions were planned for one every two years.
[src:laravel/laravel] Laravel 5.3 was released on August 23, 2016.
[src:laravel/laravel] The new features in 5.3 are focused on improving developer speed by adding additional out of the box improvements for common tasks.
[src:laravel/laravel] Laravel 5.4 was released on January 24, 2017, with many new features like Laravel Dusk, Laravel Mix, Blade Components and Slots, Markdown Emails, Automatic Facades, Route Improvements, Higher Order Messaging for Collections, and many others.
[src:laravel/laravel] Laravel 6 was released on September 3, 2019.
[src:laravel/laravel] It incorporated shift blueprint code generation, semantic versioning, compatibility with Laravel Vapor, improved authorization responses, improved job middleware, lazy collections, and sub-query improvements.
[src:laravel/laravel] The frontend scaffolding was removed from the main package and moved into the laravel/ui package.
[src:laravel/laravel] Laravel 7 was released on March 3, 2020, with new features like Laravel Sanctum, Custom Eloquent Casts, Blade Component Tags, Fluent String Operations and Route Model Binding Improvements.
[src:laravel/laravel] Laravel 8 was released on September 8, 2020, with new features like Laravel Jetstream, model factory classes, migration squashing, Tailwind CSS for pagination views and other usability improvements.
[src:laravel/laravel] Laravel 9 was released on February 8, 2022.
[src:laravel/laravel] Laravel 10 was released on February 14, 2023.
[src:laravel/laravel] Laravel 11 was released on March 12, 2024.
[src:laravel/laravel] It was announced on the Laravel blog and other social media, it was also discussed in detail at Laracon EU in Amsterdam on 5–6 February.
[src:laravel/laravel] Along with Laravel 11, a first-party websocket server called Laravel Reverb was released.
[src:laravel/laravel] Starting with Laravel 5 and up to Laravel 8, versions designated LTS were supported with bug fixes for 2 years and security fixes for 3 years.
[src:laravel/laravel] Other releases were supported with bug fixes for 6 months and security fixes for 1 year.
[src:laravel/laravel] As of version 8, major versions are released yearly, and the support timeline was changed to provide every version with 18 months of bugfixes and 2 years of security fixes.
[src:laravel/laravel] For additional libraries, only the latest major release receives bug fixes.
[src:laravel/laravel] While the numerous Laracon conferences are officially run, a number of other conferences are run under the name of Laravel Live.
[src:laravel/laravel] Currently, there are yearly held Laravel Live UK, Laravel Live Denmark, Laravel Live Pakistan and Laravel Live India conferences.
[src:laravel/laravel] While these are not officially run, they have permission from Taylor Otwell to use the name Laravel.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] In object-oriented programming, data-management tasks act on objects that combine scalar values into objects.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] For example, consider an address book entry that represents a single person along with zero or more phone numbers and zero or more addresses.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] This could be modeled in an object-oriented implementation by a "Person object" with an attribute/field to hold each data item that the entry comprises: the person's name, a list of phone numbers, and a list of addresses.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] The list of phone numbers would itself contain "PhoneNumber objects" and so on.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] Each such address-book entry is treated as a single object by the programming language (it can be referenced by a single variable containing a pointer to the object, for instance).
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] Various methods can be associated with the object, such as methods to return the preferred phone number, the home address, and so on.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] By contrast, relational databases, such as SQL, group scalars into tuples, which are then enumerated in tables.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] Tuples and objects have some general similarity, in that they are both ways to collect values into named fields such that the whole collection can be manipulated as a single compound entity.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] They have many differences, though, in particular: lifecycle management (row insertion and deletion, versus garbage collection or reference counting), references to other entities (object references, versus foreign key references), and inheritance (non-existent in relational databases).
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] As well, objects are managed on-heap and are under full control of a single process, while database tuples are shared and must incorporate locking, merging, and retry.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] Object–relational mapping provides automated support for mapping tuples to objects and back, while accounting for all of these differences.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] The heart of the problem involves translating the logical representation of the objects into an atomized form that is capable of being stored in the database while preserving the properties of the objects and their relationships so that they can be reloaded as objects when needed.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] If this storage and retrieval functionality is implemented, the objects are said to be persistent.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] Implementation-specific details of storage drivers are generally wrapped in an API in the programming language in use, exposing methods to interact with the storage medium in a way which is simpler and more in line with the paradigms of surrounding code.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] The following is a simple example, written in C# code, to execute a query written in SQL using a database engine.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] In contrast, the following makes use of an ORM-job API which makes it possible to write code that naturally makes use of the features of the language.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] The case above makes use of an object representing the storage repository and methods of that object.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] Other frameworks might provide code as static methods, as in the example below, and yet other methods may not implement an object-oriented system at all.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] Often the choice of paradigm is made for the best fit of the ORM into the surrounding language's design principles.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] Compared to traditional techniques of exchange between an object-oriented language and a relational database, ORM often reduces the amount of code that needs to be written.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] Disadvantages of ORM tools generally stem from the high level of abstraction obscuring what is actually happening in the implementation code.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] Another approach is to use an object-oriented database management system (OODBMS) or document-oriented databases such as native XML databases that provide more flexibility in data modeling.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] OODBMSs are databases designed specifically for working with object-oriented values.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] Using an OODBMS eliminates the need for converting data to and from its SQL form, as the data is stored in its original object representation and relationships are directly represented, rather than requiring join tables/operations.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] The equivalent of ORMs for document-oriented databases are called object-document mappers (ODMs).
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] Document-oriented databases also prevent the user from having to "shred" objects into table rows.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] Many of these systems also support the XQuery query language to retrieve datasets.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] Object-oriented databases tend to be used in complex, niche applications.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] One of the arguments against using an OODBMS is that it may not be able to execute ad-hoc, application-independent queries.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] For this reason, many programmers find themselves more at home with an object-SQL mapping system, even though most object-oriented databases are able to process SQL queries to a limited extent.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] Other OODBMS provide replication to SQL databases, as a means of addressing the need for ad-hoc queries, while preserving well-known query patterns.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] A variety of difficulties arise when considering how to match an object system to a relational database.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] These difficulties are referred to as the object–relational impedance mismatch.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] An alternative to implementing ORM is use of the native procedural languages provided with every major database.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] These can be called from the client using SQL statements.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] The Data Access Object (DAO) design pattern is used to abstract these statements and offer a lightweight object-oriented interface to the rest of the application.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] ORMs are limited to their predefined functionality, which may not cover all edge cases or database features.
[src:laravel/object-relational-mapping] They usually mitigate this limitation by providing users with an interface to write raw queries, such as Django ORM.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP code is usually processed on a web server by a PHP interpreter implemented as a module, a daemon or a Common Gateway Interface (CGI) executable.
[src:laravel/php-p01] On a web server, the result of the interpreted and executed PHP code—which may be any type of data, such as generated HTML or binary image data—can form the whole or part of an HTTP response.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Various web template systems, web content management systems, and web frameworks exist that can be employed to orchestrate or facilitate the generation of that response.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP can be used for programming tasks outside the web context, though non-web uses are rare.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP code can also be directly executed from the command line.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The standard PHP interpreter, powered by the Zend Engine, is free software released under the PHP License.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP has been widely ported and can be deployed on most web servers on a variety of operating systems and platforms.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The PHP language at first evolved without a written formal specification or standard, with the original implementation acting as the *de facto* standard that other implementations aimed to follow.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP development began in 1993 when Rasmus Lerdorf wrote several Common Gateway Interface (CGI) programs in C, which he used to maintain his personal homepage.
[src:laravel/php-p01] He extended them to work with HTML forms and to communicate with databases, and called this implementation "Personal Home Page/Forms Interpreter" or PHP/FI.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP/FI could be used to build simple, dynamic web applications.
[src:laravel/php-p01] To accelerate bug reporting and improve the code, Lerdorf initially announced the release of PHP/FI as "Personal Home Page Tools (PHP Tools) version 1.0" on the Usenet discussion group *comp.infosystems.www.authoring.cgi* on 8 June 1995.
[src:laravel/php-p01] This release included basic functionality such as Perl-like variables, form handling, and the ability to embed HTML.
[src:laravel/php-p01] By this point, the syntax had changed to resemble that of Perl, but was simpler, more limited, and less consistent.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The fact that PHP was not originally designed, but instead was developed organically has led to inconsistent naming of functions and inconsistent ordering of their parameters.
[src:laravel/php-p01] In some cases, the function names were chosen to match the lower-level libraries which PHP was "wrapping", while in some very early versions of PHP the length of the function names was used internally as a hash function, so names were chosen to improve the distribution of hash values.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Zeev Suraski and Andi Gutmans rewrote the parser in 1997 and formed the base of PHP 3, changing the language's name to the recursive acronym *PHP: Hypertext Preprocessor*.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Afterwards, public testing of PHP 3 began, and the official launch came in June 1998.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Suraski and Gutmans then started a new rewrite of PHP's core, producing the Zend Engine in 1999.
[src:laravel/php-p01] They also founded Zend Technologies in Ramat Gan, Israel.
[src:laravel/php-p01] On 22 May 2000, PHP 4.0, powered by the Zend Engine 1.0, was released.
[src:laravel/php-p01] By August 2008, this branch had reached version 4.4.9.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP 4 is now no longer under development nor are any security updates planned to be released.
[src:laravel/php-p01] On 1 July 2004, PHP 5.0 was released, powered by the new Zend Engine 2.0.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP 5.0 included significant changes to the language, most notably an overhauled approach to object-oriented programming, as well as iterators and exceptions.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP 5.1 and PHP 5.2 were released the following years, adding smaller improvements and new features, such as the PHP Data Objects (PDO) extension (which defines a lightweight and consistent interface for accessing databases) In 2008, PHP 5.x became the only stable version under development.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Many high-profile open-source projects ceased to support PHP 4 in new code from February 5, 2008, because of the GoPHP5 initiative, provided by a consortium of PHP developers promoting the transition from PHP 4 to PHP 5.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP's native string functions worked only on raw bytes, making use with multibyte character encodings difficult.
[src:laravel/php-p01] In 2005, a project headed by Andrei Zmievski was initiated to bring native Unicode support throughout PHP, by embedding the International Components for Unicode (ICU) library, and representing text strings as UTF-16 internally.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Since this would cause major changes both to the internals of the language and to user code, it was planned to release this as version 6.0 of the language, along with other major features then in development.
[src:laravel/php-p01] However, a shortage of developers who understood the necessary changes, and performance problems arising from conversion to and from UTF-16, which is rarely used in a web context, led to delays in the project.
[src:laravel/php-p01] As a result, a PHP 5.3 release was created in 2009, and in March 2010, the project in its current form was officially abandoned, and a PHP 5.4 release was prepared to contain most remaining non-Unicode features from PHP 6.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Initial hopes were that a new plan would be formed for Unicode integration, but by 2014 none had been adopted.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Because it contained features originally intended to be part of 6.0, PHP 5.3 was a significant release, adding support for namespaces, closures, late static binding, and many fixes and improvements to standard functions.
[src:laravel/php-p01] With the Unicode branch officially abandoned, a new release process was adopted in 2011, planning a yearly release cycle, and a clear distinction between "feature releases" (x.y.z to x.y+1.z) and "major releases" (x.y.z to x+1.0.0).
[src:laravel/php-p01] Remaining features which had been planned for the 6.0 release were included in PHP 5.4, released in March 2012, such as trait support and a new "short array syntax".
[src:laravel/php-p01] This was followed by more incremental changes in PHP 5.5 (June 2013) and 5.6 (August 2014).
[src:laravel/php-p01] For PHP versions 5.3 and 5.4, the only available Microsoft Windows binary distributions were 32-bit IA-32 builds, requiring Windows 32-bit compatibility mode while using Internet Information Services (IIS) on a 64-bit Windows platform.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP version 5.5 made the 64-bit x86-64 builds available for Microsoft Windows.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Official security support for PHP 5.6 ended on 31 December 2018.
[src:laravel/php-p01] During 2014 and 2015, a new major PHP version was developed, PHP 7.0.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The numbering of this version involved some debate among internal developers.
[src:laravel/php-p01] While the PHP 6 Unicode experiments had never been released, several articles and book titles referenced the PHP 6 names, which might have caused confusion if a new release were to reuse the name.
[src:laravel/php-p01] After a vote, the name PHP 7 was chosen.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The foundation of PHP 7.0 was a PHP branch that was originally dubbed *PHP next generation* (*phpng*).
[src:laravel/php-p01] It was written by Dmitry Stogov, Xinchen Hui and Nikita Popov, and aimed to optimize PHP performance by refactoring the Zend Engine while retaining near-complete language compatibility.
[src:laravel/php-p01] By 14 July 2014, WordPress-based benchmarks, which served as the main benchmark suite for the phpng project, showed an almost 100% increase in performance.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Changes from phpng make it easier to improve performance in future versions, as more compact data structures and other changes are seen as better suited for a successful migration to a just-in-time (JIT) compiler.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Because of the significant changes, the reworked Zend Engine was called *Zend Engine 3*, succeeding Zend Engine 2 used in PHP 5.x.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP 7.0 also included changes which were not backward compatible, as allowed for "major versions" under the versioning scheme agreed in 2011.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Changes to the core language included a more consistent handling of variable dereferencing, a more predictable behavior of the `foreach` statement, and platform consistency of bitwise shifts and floating-point to integer conversion.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Several unmaintained or deprecated server application programming interfaces (SAPIs) and extensions were removed from the PHP core, most notably the legacy `mysql` extension.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Other legacy features were also removed, such as ASP-style delimiters `<%` and `%>` and `<script language="php"> ... </script>`.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP 7.0 marked the beginning of an expansion in PHP's type system.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP 8.0 was released on 26 November 2020, as a major version with breaking changes from previous versions.
[src:laravel/php-p01] One of the most high-profile changes was the addition of a JIT compiler, which can provide substantial performance improvements for some use cases.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Substantial improvements were expected more for mathematical-type operations than for common web-development use cases.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Additionally, the performance advantage of the JIT compiler provides the potential to move some code from C to PHP.
[src:laravel/php-p01] A significant addition to the language in 8.0 is attributes, which allow metadata to be added to program elements such as classes, methods, and parameters.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Later versions added built-in attributes which change the behaviour of the language, such as the `#[\SensitiveParameter]` attribute in PHP 8.2, `#[\Override]` in PHP 8.3, `#[\Deprecated]` in PHP 8.4, and the `#[\NoDiscard]` and `#[\DelayedTargetValidation]` attributes in PHP 8.5.
[src:laravel/php-p01] A significant extension to the language's type system is the addition of composite types: union types in PHP 8.0 (e.g.
[src:laravel/php-p01] `int|string` meaning "either integer or string"), intersection types in PHP 8.1 (e.g.
[src:laravel/php-p01] `Traversable&Countable` meaning the value must implement both the `Traversable` and `Countable` interfaces), and disjunctive normal form (DNF) types in PHP 8.2 (unions of intersections, such as `array|(Traversable&Countable)`).
[src:laravel/php-p01] Additional special type keywords have been added, such as `mixed` and `static` in PHP 8.0, `never` (a bottom type indicating that a function never returns) in PHP 8.1, and `null`, `false`, and `true` as stand-alone types in PHP 8.2.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The addition of a rich type system is part of a general trend towards a stricter language, and PHP 8.0 included breaking changes to the handling of string to number comparisons, numeric strings, and incompatible method signatures.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Later versions have introduced deprecation notices for behaviour which is planned as a breaking change in a future major version, such as passing `null` to non-nullable internal function parameters and referring to properties which have not been declared on the class.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Beginning on 28 June 2011, the PHP Development Team implemented a timeline for the release of new versions of PHP.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Under this system, at least one release should occur every month.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Once per year, a minor release should occur which may include new features.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Every minor release should at least be supported for two years with security and bug fixes, followed by at least one year of only security fixes, for a total of a three-year release process for every minor release.
[src:laravel/php-p01] No new features, unless small and self-contained, are to be introduced into a minor release during the three-year release process.
[src:laravel/php-p01] A 2024 RFC extended the length of the security fix only period to two years, fixed all end of life dates to 31 December, and removed the exception that allowed for "small and self-contained" features to be introduced in patch versions.
[src:laravel/php-p01] W3Techs reports that as of November 2025 (about three years since PHP 7 was discontinued and 23 months after the PHP 8.3 release), unsupported versions such as PHP 7 are still used by well over half of PHP websites, which are outdated and known to be insecure.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Those included the 9.7% of PHP websites using the even more outdated (discontinued for 7 years) and insecure PHP 5, released over two decades ago.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The mascot of the PHP project is the *elePHPant*, a blue elephant with the PHP logo on its side, designed by Vincent Pontier in 1998.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The elePHPant is sometimes differently coloured when in plush toy form.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Many variations of this physical mascot have been made over the years.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Only the elePHPants based on the original design by Vincent Pontier are considered official by the community.
[src:laravel/php-p01] These are collectable and some of them are extremely rare.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The PHP interpreter only executes PHP code within its delimiters.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Anything outside its delimiters is not processed by PHP, although the non-PHP text can still be subject to control structures described in PHP code.
[src:laravel/php-p01] `<?php` is used to open and `?>` to close PHP sections.
[src:laravel/php-p01] A shorthand `<?=` exists, which is a shorthand for `<?php echo`.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The shortened form `<?` also exists, which makes script files less portable since support can be disabled in the local PHP configuration.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The shortened form is discouraged by the PHP Group for this reason.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Conversely, there is no recommendation against the echo short tag `<?=`.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Prior to PHP 5.4.0, the short syntax for `echo` only works with the `short_open_tag` configuration setting enabled, while for PHP 5.4.0 and later it is always available.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The purpose of delimiters is to separate PHP code from non-PHP content, such as JavaScript code or HTML markup.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The first form of delimiters, `<?php` and `?>`, in XHTML and other XML documents, creates correctly formed XML processing instructions.
[src:laravel/php-p01] This means that the resulting mixture of PHP code and other markup in the server-side file is itself well-formed XML.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Variables are prefixed with a dollar symbol, and a type does not need to be specified in advance.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP 5 introduced type declarations that allow functions to force their parameters to be objects of a specific class, arrays, interfaces or callback functions.
[src:laravel/php-p01] However, before PHP 7, type declarations could not be used with scalar types such as integers or strings.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Below is an example of how PHP variables are declared and initialized.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Unlike function and class names, variable names are case-sensitive.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Both double-quoted ("") and heredoc strings provide the ability to interpolate a variable's value into the string.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP treats newlines as whitespace in the manner of a free-form language, and statements are terminated by a semicolon.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP has three types of comments: `/* */` marks block and inline comments; `//` or `#` are used for one-line comments.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The `echo` statement is one of several keywords PHP provides to output text.
[src:laravel/php-p01] In terms of keywords and language syntax, PHP is similar to C-style syntax.
[src:laravel/php-p01] `if` conditions, `for` and `while` loops and function returns are similar in syntax to languages such as C, C++, C#, Java and Perl.
[src:laravel/php-p01] It stores integers in a platform-dependent range, either as a 32, 64 or 128-bit signed integer equivalent to the C-language long type.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Unsigned integers are converted to signed values in certain situations, which is different behaviour to many other programming languages.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Integer variables can be assigned using decimal (positive and negative), octal, hexadecimal, and binary notations.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Floating-point numbers are also stored in a platform-specific range.
[src:laravel/php-p01] They can be specified using floating-point notation, or two forms of scientific notation.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP has a native Boolean type that is similar to the native Boolean types in Java and C++.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Using the Boolean type conversion rules, non-zero values are interpreted as true and zero as false, as in Perl and C++.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The null data type represents a variable that has no value; `NULL` is the only allowed value for this data type.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Variables of the "resource" type represent references to resources from external sources.
[src:laravel/php-p01] These are typically created by functions from a particular extension, and can only be processed by functions from the same extension; examples include file, image, and database resources.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Arrays can contain elements of any type that PHP can handle, including resources, objects, and even other arrays.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Order is preserved in lists of values and in hashes with both keys and values, and the two can be intermingled.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP also supports strings, which can be used with single quotes, double quotes, nowdoc or heredoc syntax.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The **Standard PHP Library** (SPL) attempts to solve standard problems and implements efficient data access interfaces and classes.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP defines a large array of functions in the core language and many are also available in various extensions; these functions are well documented online PHP documentation.
[src:laravel/php-p01] However, the built-in library has a wide variety of naming conventions and associated inconsistencies, as described under history above.
[src:laravel/php-p01] In lieu of function pointers, functions in PHP can be referenced by a string containing their name.
[src:laravel/php-p01] In this manner, normal PHP functions can be used, for example, as callbacks or within function tables.
[src:laravel/php-p01] User-defined functions may be created at any time without being prototyped.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Functions may be defined inside code blocks, permitting a run-time decision as to whether or not a function should be defined.
[src:laravel/php-p01] There is a `function_exists` function that determines whether a function with a given name has already been defined.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Function calls must use parentheses, with the exception of zero-argument class constructor functions called with the PHP operator `new`, in which case parentheses are optional.
[src:laravel/php-p01] In the example above, `getAdder()` function creates a closure using passed argument `$x`, which takes an additional argument `$y`, and returns the created closure to the caller.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Such a function is a first-class object, meaning that it can be stored in a variable, passed as a parameter to other functions, etc.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Unusually for a dynamically typed language, PHP supports type declarations on function parameters, which are enforced at runtime.
[src:laravel/php-p01] This has been supported for classes and interfaces since PHP 5.0, for arrays since PHP 5.1, for "callables" since PHP 5.4, and scalar (integer, float, string and boolean) types since PHP 7.0.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP 7.0 also has type declarations for function return types, expressed by placing the type name after the list of parameters, preceded by a colon.
[src:laravel/php-p01] By default, scalar type declarations follow weak typing principles.
[src:laravel/php-p01] So, for example, if a parameter's type is `int`, PHP would allow not only integers, but also convertible numeric strings, floats or Booleans to be passed to that function, and would convert them.
[src:laravel/php-p01] However, PHP 7 has a "strict typing" mode which, when used, disallows such conversions for function calls and returns within a file.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Basic object-oriented programming functionality was added in PHP 3 and improved in PHP 4.
[src:laravel/php-p01] This allowed for PHP to gain further abstraction, making creative tasks easier for programmers using the language.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Object handling was completely rewritten for PHP 5, expanding the feature set and enhancing performance.
[src:laravel/php-p01] In previous versions of PHP, objects were handled like value types.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The drawback of this method was that code had to make heavy use of PHP's "reference" variables if it wanted to modify an object it was passed rather than creating a copy of it.
[src:laravel/php-p01] In the new approach, objects are referenced by handle, and not by value.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP 5 introduced private and protected member variables and methods, along with abstract classes, final classes, abstract methods, and final methods.
[src:laravel/php-p01] It also introduced a standard way of declaring constructors and destructors, similar to that of other object-oriented languages such as C++, and a standard exception handling model.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Furthermore, PHP 5 added interfaces and allowed for multiple interfaces to be implemented.
[src:laravel/php-p01] There are special interfaces that allow objects to interact with the runtime system.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Objects implementing ArrayAccess can be used with array syntax and objects implementing Iterator or IteratorAggregate can be used with the `foreach` language construct.
[src:laravel/php-p01] There is no virtual table feature in the engine, so static variables are bound with a name instead of a reference at compile time.
[src:laravel/php-p01] If the developer creates a copy of an object using the reserved word `clone`, the Zend engine will check whether a `__clone()` method has been defined.
[src:laravel/php-p01] If not, it will call a default `__clone()` which will copy the object's properties.
[src:laravel/php-p01] If a `__clone()` method is defined, then it will be responsible for setting the necessary properties in the created object.
[src:laravel/php-p01] For convenience, the engine will supply a function that imports the properties of the source object, so the programmer can start with a by-value replica of the source object and only override properties that need to be changed.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The visibility of PHP properties and methods is defined using the keywords `public`, `private`, and `protected`.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The default is public, if only var is used; `var` is a synonym for `public`.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Items declared `public` can be accessed everywhere.
[src:laravel/php-p01] `protected` limits access to inherited classes (and to the class that defines the item).
[src:laravel/php-p01] `private` limits visibility only to the class that defines the item.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Objects of the same type have access to each other's private and protected members even though they are not the same instance.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The only complete PHP implementation is the original, known simply as PHP.
[src:laravel/php-p01] It is the most widely used and is powered by the Zend Engine.
[src:laravel/php-p01] To disambiguate it from other implementations, it is sometimes unofficially called "Zend PHP".
[src:laravel/php-p01] The Zend Engine compiles PHP source code on-the-fly into an internal format that it can execute, thus it works as an interpreter.
[src:laravel/php-p01] It is also the "reference implementation" of PHP, as PHP has no formal specification, and so the semantics of Zend PHP define the semantics of PHP.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Due to the complex and nuanced semantics of PHP, defined by how Zend works, it is difficult for competing implementations to offer complete compatibility.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP's single-request-per-script-execution model, and the fact that the Zend Engine is an interpreter, leads to inefficiency; as a result, various products have been developed to help improve PHP performance.
[src:laravel/php-p01] An opcode cache, Zend Opcache, is built into PHP since version 5.5.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Another example of a widely used opcode cache is the Alternative PHP Cache (APC), which is available as a PECL extension.
[src:laravel/php-p01] While Zend PHP is still the most popular implementation, several other implementations have been developed.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Some of these are compilers or support JIT compilation, and hence offer performance benefits over Zend PHP at the expense of lacking full PHP compatibility.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP is free software released under the PHP License, which is equivalent to the 3-clause BSD license.
[src:laravel/php-p01] This restriction on the use of "PHP" made the PHP License incompatible with the GNU General Public License (GPL), while the Zend License was incompatible due to an advertising clause similar to that of the original BSD license.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP includes various free and open-source libraries in its source distribution or uses them in resulting PHP binary builds.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP is fundamentally an Internet-aware system with built-in modules for accessing File Transfer Protocol (FTP) servers and many database servers, including PostgreSQL, MySQL, Microsoft SQL Server and SQLite (which is an embedded database), LDAP servers, and others.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Numerous functions are familiar to C programmers, such as those in the stdio family, are available in standard PHP builds.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP allows developers to write extensions in C to add functionality to the PHP language.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP extensions can be compiled statically into PHP or loaded dynamically at runtime.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Numerous extensions have been written to add support for the Windows API, process management on Unix-like operating systems, multibyte strings (Unicode), cURL, and several popular compression formats.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Other PHP features made available through extensions include integration with Internet Relay Chat (IRC), dynamic generation of images and Adobe Flash content, *PHP Data Objects* (PDO) as an abstraction layer used for accessing databases, and even speech synthesis.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Some of the language's core functions, such as those dealing with strings and arrays, are also implemented as extensions.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The PHP Extension Community Library (PECL) project is a repository for extensions to the PHP language.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Most of the community focuses on web development, and PHP running server side (though also serving JavaScript for the client side), and some exceptional uses are for e.g. standalone graphical applications (with PHP-GTK unmaintained now for over a decade), and even drone control.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Some other projects, such as *Zephir*, provide the ability for PHP extensions to be created in a high-level language and compiled into native PHP extensions.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Such an approach, instead of writing PHP extensions directly in C, simplifies the development of extensions and reduces the time required for programming and testing.
[src:laravel/php-p01] By December 2018 the PHP Group consisted of ten people: Thies C.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Arntzen, Stig Bakken, Shane Caraveo, Andi Gutmans, Rasmus Lerdorf, Sam Ruby, Sascha Schumann, Zeev Suraski, Jim Winstead, and Andrei Zmievski.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Zend Technologies provides a PHP Certification based on PHP 8 exam (and previously based on PHP 7 and 5.5) for programmers to become certified PHP developers.
[src:laravel/php-p01] On 26 November 2021, the JetBrains blog announced the creation of The PHP Foundation, which will sponsor the design and development of PHP.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The foundation hires "Core Developers" to work on the PHP language's core repository.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Roman Pronskiy, a member of the foundation's board, said that they aim to pay "market salaries" to developers.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The response to the foundation has been largely positive.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Germany's Sovereign Tech Fund provided more than 200,000 Euros to support the PHP Foundation.
[src:laravel/php-p01] There are two primary ways for adding support for PHP to a web server – as a native web server module, or as a CGI executable.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP has a direct module interface called server application programming interface (SAPI), which is supported by many web servers including Apache HTTP Server, Microsoft IIS, Caddy (through FrankenPHP) and iPlanet Web Server.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Some other web servers, such as OmniHTTPd, support the Internet Server Application Programming Interface (ISAPI), which is Microsoft's web server module interface.
[src:laravel/php-p01] If PHP has no module support for a web server, it can always be used as a Common Gateway Interface (CGI) or FastCGI processor; in that case, the web server is configured to use PHP's CGI executable to process all requests to PHP files.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP-FPM (FastCGI Process Manager) is an alternative FastCGI implementation for PHP, bundled with the official PHP distribution since version 5.3.3.
[src:laravel/php-p01] When compared to the older FastCGI implementation, it contains some additional features, mostly useful for heavily loaded web servers.
[src:laravel/php-p01] When using PHP for command-line scripting, a PHP command-line interface (CLI) executable is needed.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP supports a CLI server application programming interface (SAPI) since PHP 4.3.0.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The main focus of this SAPI is developing shell applications using PHP.
[src:laravel/php-p01] There are quite a few differences between the CLI SAPI and other SAPIs, although they do share many of the same behaviours.
[src:laravel/php-p01] There are different kinds of SAPIs for various web server extensions.
[src:laravel/php-p01] For example, in addition to those listed above, other SAPIs for the PHP language include the Common Gateway Interface and command-line interface.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP can also be used for writing desktop graphical user interface (GUI) applications, by using the *"PHP Desktop".
[src:laravel/php-p01] *GitHub*.* or discontinued PHP-GTK extension.
[src:laravel/php-p01] PHP-GTK is not included in the official PHP distribution, and as an extension, it can be used only with PHP versions 5.1.0 and newer.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The most common way of installing PHP-GTK is by compiling it from the source code.
[src:laravel/php-p01] When PHP is installed and used in cloud environments, software development kits (SDKs) are provided for using cloud-specific features.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Numerous configuration options are supported, affecting both core PHP features and extensions.
[src:laravel/php-p01] Configuration file `php.ini` is searched for in different locations, depending on the way PHP is used.
[src:laravel/php-p01] The configuration file is split into various sections, while some of the configuration options can be also set within the web server configuration.
[src:laravel/php-p02] PHP is a general-purpose scripting language that is especially suited to server-side web development, in which case PHP generally runs on a web server.
[src:laravel/php-p02] Any PHP code in a requested file is executed by the PHP runtime, usually to create dynamic web page content or dynamic images used on websites or elsewhere.
[src:laravel/php-p02] It can also be used for command-line scripting and client-side graphical user interface (GUI) applications.
[src:laravel/php-p02] PHP can be deployed on most web servers, many operating systems and platforms, and can be used with many relational database management systems (RDBMS).
[src:laravel/php-p02] Most web hosting providers support PHP for use by their clients.
[src:laravel/php-p02] It is available free of charge, and the PHP Group provides the complete source code for users to build, customize and extend for their own use.
[src:laravel/php-p02] PHP has also attracted the development of many software frameworks that provide building blocks and a design structure to promote rapid application development (RAD).
[src:laravel/php-p02] Some of these include PRADO, CakePHP, Symfony, CodeIgniter, Laravel, Yii Framework, Phalcon and Laminas, offering features similar to other web frameworks.
[src:laravel/php-p02] The LAMP architecture has become popular in the web industry as a way of deploying web applications.
[src:laravel/php-p02] PHP is commonly used as the *P* in this bundle alongside Linux, Apache and MySQL, although the *P* may also refer to Python, Perl, or some mix of the three.
[src:laravel/php-p02] Similar packages, WAMP and MAMP, are also available for Windows and macOS, with the first letter standing for the respective operating system.
[src:laravel/php-p02] Although both PHP and Apache are provided as part of the macOS base install, users of these packages seek a simpler installation mechanism that can be more easily kept up to date.
[src:laravel/php-p02] For specific and more advanced usage scenarios, PHP offers a well-defined and documented way for writing custom extensions in C or C++.
[src:laravel/php-p02] Besides extending the language itself in form of additional libraries, extensions are providing a way for improving execution speed where it is critical and there is room for improvements by using a true compiled language.
[src:laravel/php-p02] PHP also offers well-defined ways for embedding itself into other software projects.
[src:laravel/php-p02] That way PHP can be easily used as an internal scripting language for another project, also providing tight interfacing with the project's specific internal data structures.
[src:laravel/php-p02] PHP received mixed reviews due to lacking support for multithreading at the core language level, though using threads is made possible by the "pthreads" PECL extension.
[src:laravel/php-p02] A command line interface, php-cli, and two ActiveX Windows Script Host scripting engines for PHP have been produced.
[src:laravel/php-p02] PHP is used for Web content management systems including MediaWiki, WordPress, Joomla, Drupal, Moodle, eZ Publish, eZ Platform, and SilverStripe.
[src:laravel/php-p02] As of January 2013, PHP was used in more than 240 million websites (39% of those sampled) and was installed on 2.1 million web servers.
[src:laravel/php-p02] In 2019, 11% of all vulnerabilities listed by the National Vulnerability Database were linked to PHP; historically, about 30% of all vulnerabilities listed since 1996 in this database are linked to PHP.
[src:laravel/php-p02] Technical security flaws of the language itself or of its core libraries are not frequent (22 in 2009, about 1% of the total although PHP applies to about 20% of programs listed).
[src:laravel/php-p02] Recognizing that programmers make mistakes, some languages include taint checking to automatically detect the lack of input validation which induces many issues.
[src:laravel/php-p02] Such a feature has been proposed for PHP in the past, but either been rejected or the proposal abandoned.
[src:laravel/php-p02] Third-party projects such as Suhosin and Snuffleupagus aim to remove or change dangerous parts of the language.
[src:laravel/php-p02] Historically, old versions of PHP had some configuration parameters and default values for such runtime settings that made some PHP applications prone to security issues.
[src:laravel/php-p02] Support for "magic quotes" and "register globals" settings has been deprecated since PHP 5.3.0, and removed from PHP 5.4.0.
[src:laravel/php-p02] The best practice is to either locate the image directory outside the document root available to the web server and serve it via an intermediary script or disable PHP execution for the directory which stores the uploaded files.
[src:laravel/php-p02] Also, enabling the dynamic loading of PHP extensions (via `enable_dl` configuration directive) in a shared web hosting environment can lead to security issues.
[src:laravel/php-p02] Implied type conversions that result in different values being treated as equal, sometimes against the programmer's intent, can lead to security issues.
[src:laravel/php-p02] For example, the result of the comparison `'0e1234' == '0'` is `true`, because strings that are parsable as numbers are converted to numbers; in this case, the first compared value is treated as scientific notation having the value (0×101234), which is zero.
[src:laravel/php-p02] Errors like this resulted in authentication vulnerabilities in Simple Machines Forum, Typo3 and phpBB when MD5 password hashes were compared.
[src:laravel/php-p02] The recommended way is to use `hash_equals()` (for timing attack safety), `strcmp` or the identity operator (`===`), as `'0e1234' === '0'` results in `false`.
[src:laravel/php-p02] In a 2013 analysis of over 170,000 website defacements, published by Zone-H, the most frequently (53%) used technique was the exploitation of file inclusion vulnerability, mostly related to insecure usage of the PHP language constructs `include`, `require`, and `allow_url_fopen`.
[src:laravel/php-p02] PHP includes `rand()` and `mt_rand()` functions which use a pseudorandom number generator, and are not cryptographically secure.
[src:laravel/php-p02] As of version 8.1, the `random_int()` function is included, which uses a cryptographically secure source of randomness provided by the system.
[src:laravel/php-p02] There are two attacks that can be performed over PHP entropy sources: "seed attack" and "state recovery attack".
[src:laravel/php-p02] As of 2012, a $250 GPU can perform up to 230 MD5 calculations per second, while a $750 GPU can perform four times as many calculations at the same time.
[src:laravel/php-p02] In combination with a "birthday attack" this can lead to serious security vulnerabilities.
[src:laravel/php-p02] The PHP development team provides official bug fixes for two years following release of each minor version followed by another two years where only security fixes are released.
[src:laravel/php-p02] After this, the release is considered end of life and no longer officially supported.
